	<h2>What Is Ear Wax and Why Does It Build Up?</h2>
	<p>
		Ear wax (cerumen) is naturally produced by glands in the ear canal and
		plays an important role in protecting and cleaning the ear. In most cases,
		it generally works its way out of the ear on its own. However, certain
		factors can contribute to wax building up more quickly or becoming
		impacted, including:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Genetics</li>
		<li>Regular use of hearing aids or earbuds</li>
		<li>Narrow or naturally curved ear canals</li>
		<li>Dry skin conditions such as eczema</li>
		<li>A history of frequent ear infections</li>
		<li>Naturally higher wax production</li>
		<li>Use of cotton swabs or other at-home cleaning tools</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		When wax builds up faster than the ear can clear it, it may become impacted
		and lead to symptoms such as muffled hearing, fullness, or discomfort.
	</p>

	<h2>Signs of Excess Ear Wax or a Blockage</h2>
	<p>You may have a wax blockage if you notice:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Muffled or reduced hearing</li>
		<li>Ear pain, fullness or pressure</li>
		<li>Tinnitus (ringing or buzzing in the ear)</li>
		<li>Itching or irritation in the ear canal</li>
		<li>Dizziness or a sense of imbalance</li>
		<li>Coughing triggered by ear canal pressure</li>
		<li>Feedback or whistling in your hearing aids</li>
		<li>Reduced performance of the hearing aids</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		If any of these symptoms sound familiar, a visit with an audiologist can
		quickly determine whether ear wax is the cause and provide safe, effective
		relief.
	</p>

	<h2>Safe At-Home Ear Wax Removal Techniques</h2>
	<p>
		Ear wax softening agents—often called cerumenolytics—can be a helpful and
		safe first step when used appropriately. These over-the-counter drops are
		designed to gently break down and loosen hardened ear wax, making it easier
		for the body to naturally clear it or for a clinician to remove it more
		comfortably and effectively.
	</p>
	<p>When used correctly, softening agents can:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Help reduce mild wax buildup before it becomes impacted</li>
		<li>Support the ear's natural self-cleaning process</li>
		<li>Decrease the need for more invasive removal methods in some cases</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		However, proper use is important. These drops should only be used when
		there is no known eardrum perforation, active ear infection, or ear tubes
		in place. Overuse or use in the wrong situation may cause irritation or
		delay appropriate treatment.
	</p>
	<p>
		If symptoms such as muffled hearing, pressure, or discomfort persist after
		using softening drops, it's important to have the ears evaluated. A
		professional can determine whether wax is the cause and safely remove it if
		needed—ensuring both comfort and ear health are protected.
	</p>

	<h2>Unsafe At-Home Ear Wax Removal Techniques</h2>
	<p>
		At-home tools such as cotton swabs, hairpins, and ear candles may seem like
		a quick fix, but they often cause more harm than good.
	</p>
	<p>Common risks include:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Pushing wax deeper into the ear canal</li>
		<li>Scratching or irritating the delicate skin of the ear canal</li>
		<li>Potentially damaging or perforating the eardrum</li>
		<li>Burns or injury from ear candling</li>
		<li>Worsening an existing wax blockage</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		For safe at-home care, it's best to gently wipe only the outer ear with a
		damp cloth or use over-the-counter drops designed to soften ear wax. If
		symptoms continue or the blockage does not clear on its own, professional
		removal is the safest and most effective option.
	</p>

	<h2>Professional Ear Wax Removal at Commonwealth Audiology</h2>
	<p>
		At Commonwealth Audiology, our audiologist uses gentle, proven techniques
		to remove ear wax safely and comfortably. Depending on the type of
		blockage, we may use:
	</p>

	<h3>Manual Removal (Curette)</h3>
	<p>
		One common method is manual removal using a curette. A curette is a small,
		specially designed instrument that allows the clinician to gently lift or
		scoop wax out of the ear canal under direct visualization. This method is
		especially useful when the wax is firm and easily accessible. It requires
		precision and is performed carefully to avoid contact with the sensitive
		ear canal walls.
	</p>

	<h3>Irrigation</h3>
	<p>
		Another commonly used method is irrigation, which gently flushes the ear
		canal with warm water to help soften and remove wax. When performed in a
		clinical setting, irrigation is carefully controlled to ensure both safety
		and comfort.
	</p>
	<p>
		At Commonwealth Audiology, we often use the Earigator, a specialized
		irrigation system that regulates both water pressure and temperature. This
		level of control is important because it helps prevent irritation to the
		ear canal and reduces the risk of complications such as eardrum trauma or
		dizziness during the procedure. By maintaining consistent, body-safe
		temperature and gentle, steady pressure, the Earigator allows for a more
		comfortable and predictable experience.
	</p>

	<h3>Suction</h3>
	<p>
		A third method is suction, which uses a small, gentle vacuum device to
		remove wax while the clinician visualizes the ear canal through
		magnification. Many patients find this method particularly comfortable and
		precise, as it does not involve introducing fluid into the ear and allows
		for careful, controlled removal.
	</p>
	<p>
		At Commonwealth Audiology, the method used is always tailored to the
		individual's ear health and comfort. The goal is to safely clear the
		blockage while protecting the delicate structures of the ear and ensuring
		you leave with improved comfort and clearer hearing.
	</p>

	<h2>How Often Should Ear Wax Be Removed?</h2>
	<p>
		For most people, the ears are naturally self-cleaning, and routine wax
		removal is not necessary. However, some individuals are more prone to
		buildup and may benefit from periodic monitoring and professional care.
	</p>
	<p>You may need more frequent ear checks if you:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Wear hearing aids or earbuds regularly</li>
		<li>Experience recurring wax blockages</li>
		<li>Have naturally narrow or curved ear canals</li>
		<li>Produce a higher-than-average amount of ear wax</li>
		<li>Have skin conditions such as eczema affecting the ear canal</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		At Commonwealth Audiology, we take an individualized approach. Your
		audiologist will assess your ears and recommend a care schedule that
		supports both comfort and healthy hearing, based on your specific needs
		rather than a one-size-fits-all timeline.
	</p>

	<h2>Hearing Aids and Ear Wax</h2>
	<p>
		Ear wax buildup is one of the most common reasons hearing aids don't
		perform the way they should. Because hearing aids sit directly in or just
		outside the ear canal, they are constantly exposed to cerumen (ear wax).
		Even a small amount can make a big difference in how well sound is picked
		up and delivered.
	</p>
	<p>When wax builds up, patients often notice changes such as:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Sounds becoming muffled, distant, or "underwater"</li>
		<li>Intermittent or distorted audio that comes and goes</li>
		<li>Increased feedback or whistling</li>
		<li>A hearing aid that seems to suddenly stop working</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		In many cases, the hearing aid isn't broken at all, the device is simply
		being blocked by wax.
	</p>
	<p>
		Over time, wax can also build up unnoticed, especially for individuals who
		wear hearing aids daily. Because the devices can gently push wax deeper
		into the canal, it becomes even more important to have routine checks and
		professional cleanings to prevent long-term blockages.
	</p>

